      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions verified to within 1% for linear elastic beam bending and contact mechanics. Solver documentation confirms passing NAFEMS benchmark suite.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical passes published NAFEMS benchmark tests for structural mechanics. FDA in-house solver benchmarked against analytical Euler-Bernoulli beam solutions. Code verification artifacts reviewed and on file. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in construct stiffness and yield force QoIs between medium and fine mesh densities. Richardson extrapolation applied to confirm asymptotic convergence.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study conducted across three refinement levels (coarse, medium, fine). QoI change between medium and fine meshes was 0.8% for stiffness and 1.3% for yield force, both below 2% threshold. Richardson extrapolation confirms second-order convergence in the energy norm. Discretization error contribution to total uncertainty quantified as <1.5%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence tolerance set to 1e-6 for all nonlinear iterations. Energy convergence criterion also applied. Solver logs reviewed for all 11 simulation cases.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver convergence confirmed for all simulation runs. Force and displacement residuals converged to 1e-6 within 50 iterations for each load step. No divergence or spurious solution artifacts observed. Solver error contribution estimated at <0.1% of QoI magnitude."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and loading by a second analyst not involved in original model construction. Discrepancies resolved and documented.",
      "rationale": "Model setup reviewed independently by a second FEA engineer at each of the three modeling sites. Boundary condition application (ASTM F1717 loading fixture geometry, displacement-controlled loading rate) verified against test protocol. No use errors identified during peer review. Documentation of review on file."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear elastic material model appropriate for pre-yield regime; bilinear isotropic hardening used for post-yield. Contact formulation validated against analytical contact solutions. Model form uncertainty quantified via sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V pedicle screw modeled with bilinear isotropic hardening (E=114 GPa, yield=880 MPa, tangent modulus=1.14 GPa) consistent with ASTM F136 material specification. UHMWPE test block modeled as linear elastic (E=0.69 GPa). Augmented Lagrangian contact formulation used at screw-block interface. Model form sensitivity analysis shows <5% QoI sensitivity to ±10% variation in tangent modulus. Model form uncertainty included in total uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports for each screw lot. Geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of test specimens. Input uncertainty propagated through model via Monte Carlo sampling (N=500).",
      "rationale": "Screw geometry digitized from CMM measurements of three representative specimens from each test lot, with dimensional tolerances applied as uniform distributions. Material properties (E, yield strength) drawn from certified material test reports with normal distributions fitted to lot-level data. Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation (N=500 samples) quantifies combined input uncertainty contribution to QoI variability. Input uncertainty is the dominant uncertainty source at ~4% of QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs tested, drawn from two independent lots, across two independent laboratories. Sample size sufficient for statistical comparison per ASTM E2935.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested: six at Laboratory A (FDA), five at Laboratory B (DePuy Synthes). Constructs assembled from two independent production lots to capture inter-lot variability. Sample representativeness confirmed by dimensional inspection. Inter-laboratory reproducibility assessed via ANOVA showing no significant lab effect (p=0.31) on stiffness QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions should span at least two loading rates and two fixation torque levels to characterize sensitivity of QoIs to test setup variability.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted at a single loading rate (25 mm/min) and single fixation torque (8 Nm) per ASTM F1717 protocol. While the standard protocol was followed precisely, only one test condition was evaluated, limiting characterization of QoI sensitivity to test setup variability. This factor is below the required level 3; however, the deficiency is accepted given that ASTM F1717 prescribes a single standard condition and inter-laboratory reproducibility partially compensates. Risk accepted at team level with documented acknowledgment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) shown to be equivalent to experimental conditions within quantified tolerances for each of the 11 test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Specimen-specific FEA models constructed using CMM-measured geometry for each of the 11 test constructs. Material properties assigned from lot-certified test reports. Loading fixture geometry replicated from engineering drawings verified against physical fixture measurements. Equivalency confirmed: geometric deviation <0.05 mm, material property deviation <2% from nominal. Boundary condition equivalency verified by comparing fixture compliance in simulation vs. measured machine compliance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for each QoI (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm). Percentage difference between mean FEA prediction and mean experimental result < 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness: mean FEA 187.3 N/mm vs. mean experimental 191.8 N/mm, difference 2.3%, E/uval=0.84. Yield force: mean FEA 412.6 N vs. mean experimental 421.1 N, difference 2.0%, E/uval=1.12. Force at 40 mm: mean FEA 638.4 N vs. mean experimental 651.7 N, difference 2.0%, E/uval=1.31. All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria. Total validation uncertainty uval computed as RSS of model input uncertainty, discretization error, and experimental measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements for pedicle screw systems.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness characterizes the mechanical environment transmitted to the vertebral bodies. Yield force is the primary safety-relevant QoI, directly linked to implant fracture risk. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption. All three QoIs are mandated by ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. QoI relevance to COU confirmed by clinical and regulatory subject matter experts."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation test conditions (loading mode, specimen geometry, material, scale) match COU conditions. Any differences between validation and COU contexts are documented and their impact on model credibility assessed.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities directly replicate the COU: ASTM F1717 static compression-bending, non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, Ti-6Al-4V, full-scale geometry, UHMWPE test blocks representing vertebral bone analog. No geometric scaling or material substitution applied. The validation specimens are production-representative parts from the same design family as the COU device. Validation activity relevance assessed as high; no significant gap between validation context and COU identified."
    }
